form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sheriff of Gloucester John Alexander Walshe 2nd was born about 1450, in Olveston, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Sir John Alexander Walsh Sr., was 31 and his mother, Lady Margaret Alice De'Seymour, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Elizabeth Ann Forster. He died in 1501, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1450–1501":"umbes 1450–1501","1446–Female":"1446–Surnud","1448–Female":"1448–Surnud","1450–1501":"1450–1501","1452–Male":"1452–Surnud","1455–Female":"1455–Surnud","1474–1547":"1474–1547","1487–Male":"1487–Surnud","1420–Male":"1420–Surnud","1430–Fema